Advanced Compact High-Field REBCO Architectures for Precision Spectroscopy (AETHER)

Mathematical Design and Optimization of a 35 T, 1 ppm Homogeneous Benchtop Magnet with Dynamic Stability and Robust Buildability

Author: ouadi Maakoul 

Abstract

The recent breakthrough by ETH Zürich demonstrated a 42.3 T magnetic field in a palm‑sized device using REBCO pancake coils (Gao et al., Science Advances 12, eadz5826, 2026). While this proves the feasibility of ultra‑high fields in miniature form factors, the device suffers from critical limitations: a restricted bore (3.1 mm), field inhomogeneity exceeding 100–180 ppm over a 0.6 mm axial region, and screening current‑induced field drift of 350 ppm/h, resulting in an NMR linewidth of 270 ppm—too broad to resolve chemical shift differences. A subsequent study by the same group (Gao et al., Superconductor Science and Technology 39, 035012, 2026) experimentally characterized the dynamic evolution of pressure‑dependent turn‑to‑turn contact resistivity, revealing the critical role of mechanical–electrical coupling in no‑insulation coils.

This thesis presents Project AETHER, a comprehensive mathematical redesign of the miniature magnet architecture that directly builds upon these experimental findings. Using advanced multi‑physics mathematical modeling and numerical optimization, we derive a magnet design capable of >35 T in a 10 mm bore with <1 ppm spatial homogeneity over a 5 mm³ volume and <0.01 ppm/hour temporal drift—a specification that would enable 1.5 GHz proton Larmor frequency in a benchtop footprint. All models are derived from first principles, and the design is obtained through rigorous multi‑objective optimization with full coupling between electromagnetic, mechanical, and thermal phenomena.

The mathematical framework comprises:

· Electromagnetic field theory: Biot‑Savart law, spherical harmonic expansion for homogeneity analysis, and active shimming via inverse problem formulation.
· Screening current dynamics: H-formulation with non‑linear E(J) = E_c (J/J_c)^n power law for first‑principles temporal drift prediction, coupled with mutual inductance between pancakes.
· Mechanical stress analysis: Orthotropic elasticity tensor, equilibrium equations in cylindrical coordinates, strain‑dependent critical current degradation I_c(ε)/I_{c0} = 1 - a|ε - ε_0|^b.
· Pressure‑dependent contact resistivity: ρ_ct(σ_r) = ρ_∞ + (ρ_0 - ρ_∞) exp(β σ_r/σ_ref) coupling mechanical stress to electrical turn‑to‑turn resistance, with parameters calibrated against published experimental data.
· Functionally graded overbanding: Radially varying fiber volume fraction V_f(r) for stress redistribution, with homogenized orthotropic properties.
· Multi‑scale homogenization: Effective material properties of REBCO tape derived from layer thicknesses via rule of mixtures.
· Thermal dynamics: Heat diffusion equation with Joule heating and coupling losses, NI/MI time constants, quench propagation velocities.
· Multi‑objective optimization: NSGA‑II with six objectives (field error, homogeneity, drift, tape length, stress safety, buildability) and rigorous hypervolume convergence criterion, implemented with Gaussian process surrogates trained on full multi‑physics evaluations.

All mathematical models are derived from first principles, and the final design is presented as a complete mathematical blueprint with all geometric parameters, current distributions, shim currents, pre‑emphasis profile, overband grading function, striation pattern, and turn‑to‑turn contact resistivity target. Tolerance sensitivity maps identify critical parameters requiring precise manufacturing control. This work provides the theoretical foundation for a new class of compact, high‑performance NMR magnets.


