Appendix D: Derivation of Screening Current Relaxation Logarithmic Law

The flux creep in superconductors leads to a logarithmic decay of the magnetization and hence the field drift. Starting from the power law E = E_c (J/J_c)^n, and using the flux creep model by Anderson and Kim, the electric field is related to the flux line velocity. A simpler derivation: in a superconductor with critical state, the current density relaxes according to:

\frac{dJ}{dt} = -\frac{U_0}{k_B T} \nu_0 \exp\left(-\frac{U_0}{k_B T}\right) \sinh\left(\frac{J}{J_c} \frac{U_0}{k_B T}\right),

which for small J/J_c approximates to a logarithmic decay. More directly, from the power law and the flux conservation, one can show that the screening current decays as:

J(t) = J_0 \left(1 + \frac{n E_c}{\mu_0 J_c R} t \right)^{-1/(n-1)},

but this is valid for short times. For long times, the decay is logarithmic. In many treatments, the field drift is given by:

B(t) = B_0 - \frac{n E_c}{\mu_0 J_c R} \ln\left(1 + \frac{t}{\tau}\right),

where \tau depends on geometry and material parameters.

In the AETHER model, we use the empirical form:

B(t) = B_0 - \alpha \ln\left(1 + \frac{t}{\tau_{\text{scr}}}\right),

and determine \alpha and \tau_{\text{scr}} from numerical simulations of the H-formulation.

