Appendix F: Derivation of Orthotropic Elasticity Equations

For an orthotropic material, the generalized Hooke's law in cylindrical coordinates (with no shear coupling between normal and shear strains) is:

\begin{pmatrix}
\varepsilon_r \\ \varepsilon_\theta \\ \varepsilon_z \\ \gamma_{rz}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{1}{E_r} & -\frac{\nu_{\theta r}}{E_\theta} & -\frac{\nu_{z r}}{E_z} & 0 \\
-\frac{\nu_{r\theta}}{E_r} & \frac{1}{E_\theta} & -\frac{\nu_{z\theta}}{E_z} & 0 \\
-\frac{\nu_{rz}}{E_r} & -\frac{\nu_{\theta z}}{E_\theta} & \frac{1}{E_z} & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 0 & \frac{1}{G_{rz}}
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
\sigma_r \\ \sigma_\theta \\ \sigma_z \\ \tau_{rz}
\end{pmatrix}.

The symmetry of the compliance matrix requires:

\frac{\nu_{\theta r}}{E_\theta} = \frac{\nu_{r\theta}}{E_r}, \quad
\frac{\nu_{z r}}{E_z} = \frac{\nu_{r z}}{E_r}, \quad
\frac{\nu_{z \theta}}{E_z} = \frac{\nu_{\theta z}}{E_\theta}.

Thus only 9 independent constants: E_r, E_\theta, E_z, G_{rz}, \nu_{r\theta}, \nu_{rz}, \nu_{\theta z} (the others follow).

The equilibrium equations in cylindrical coordinates (axisymmetric, no tangential variation) are:

\frac{\partial \sigma_r}{\partial r} + \frac{\partial \tau_{rz}}{\partial z} + \frac{\sigma_r - \sigma_\theta}{r} + f_r = 0,

\frac{\partial \tau_{rz}}{\partial r} + \frac{\partial \sigma_z}{\partial z} + \frac{\tau_{rz}}{r} + f_z = 0,

where f_r, f_z are body forces (Lorentz forces). For the coil, these are:

f_r = J_\phi B_z, \quad f_z = -J_\phi B_r.

These equations are solved with appropriate boundary conditions (e.g., free surfaces, symmetry) to obtain the stress distribution.

