Appendix G: Functionally Graded Overbanding Stress Distribution

Consider a composite cylinder consisting of an inner layer (the REBCO coil) and an outer layer (the overband) with radially varying properties. The hoop stress in the coil can be derived from the condition of radial displacement continuity.

Assuming plane stress or generalized plane strain, the radial displacement u satisfies:

\frac{d}{dr}\left( \frac{1}{r} \frac{d}{dr}(r u) \right) = -\frac{1-\nu^2}{E} f_r \quad \text{(for isotropic case)}.

For orthotropic materials with cylindrical orthotropy, the equation is more complex. A simplified approach: the overband and coil are in parallel in the hoop direction, so the total hoop stress \sigma_\theta^{\text{total}} is shared according to stiffness:

\sigma_\theta^{\text{coil}}(r) = \frac{E_\theta^{\text{coil}}}{E_\theta^{\text{coil}} + E_\theta^{\text{ob}}(r)} \sigma_\theta^{\text{total}}(r).

The total hoop stress is obtained from a global equilibrium: integrating the Lorentz body force gives the net force on a cross-section, which is balanced by the hoop stress in the combined structure. For a thin ring, the hoop stress is approximately \sigma_\theta \approx J B_z r.

A more rigorous derivation uses the compatibility of radial displacement and the equilibrium equations. The radial stress \sigma_r is continuous at the interface, and the displacement u is also continuous. Solving these conditions yields the stress distribution in each layer.

In the AETHER design, the functional grading V_f(r) is chosen to minimize the peak stress in the REBCO tape while keeping the overband within its strength limits. The optimal V_f(r) is found through optimization.

