Appendix H: Contact Resistivity Model Derivation and Parameter Calibration

The pressure-dependent contact resistivity model is based on the physics of rough surface contact. When two surfaces are pressed together, the actual contact area increases with pressure, reducing the electrical contact resistance. The general form is:

R_c = \frac{\rho_{\text{surface}}}{A_{\text{contact}}},

where A_{\text{contact}} increases with pressure. A common empirical model is:

\rho_{ct} = \rho_\infty + (\rho_0 - \rho_\infty) \exp(-\beta P),

with P the contact pressure. Since \sigma_r is negative in compression, we write P = -\sigma_r (positive). Thus:

\rho_{ct}(\sigma_r) = \rho_\infty + (\rho_0 - \rho_\infty) \exp\left(\beta \frac{\sigma_r}{\sigma_{\text{ref}}}\right),

with \sigma_{\text{ref}} a scaling factor.

The parameters were calibrated using data from Gao et al. (2026b). They measured the charging time constant \tau_{\text{NI}} as a function of current. Since \tau_{\text{NI}} \propto 1/R_c \propto 1/\rho_{ct}, we can fit the model to their data. The values obtained are:

· \rho_0 = 48\ \mu\Omega\cdot\text{cm}^2 (zero-pressure resistivity)
· \rho_\infty = 1.1\ \mu\Omega\cdot\text{cm}^2 (high-pressure limit)
· \beta = 0.014 (compaction coefficient)

These values reproduce the experimental \tau_{\text{NI}} evolution within 8% over the range 0–300 A.

