Appendix J: NSGA-II Algorithm Pseudocode and Hypervolume Calculation

NSGA-II Pseudocode

```
Input: N (population size), T_max (max generations), crossover probability, mutation rate
Output: Pareto front

Initialize population P_0 of size N randomly
Evaluate objective functions for all individuals in P_0
Assign rank (nondomination level) and crowding distance
for t = 0 to T_max-1
    // Create offspring Q_t
    Q_t = empty set
    while |Q_t| < N
        Select parents p1, p2 from P_t using tournament selection (based on rank and crowding)
        Apply crossover with probability to produce children c1, c2
        Apply mutation to c1, c2
        Evaluate objectives for c1, c2
        Add c1, c2 to Q_t
    end
    // Combine parent and offspring
    R_t = P_t ∪ Q_t
    // Fast nondominated sort on R_t
    fronts = fast_nondominated_sort(R_t)
    // Select new population P_{t+1}
    P_{t+1} = empty set
    i = 1
    while |P_{t+1}| + |fronts[i]| ≤ N
        assign crowding distance to fronts[i]
        P_{t+1} = P_{t+1} ∪ fronts[i]
        i = i+1
    end
    // Sort fronts[i] by crowding distance descending
    sort(fronts[i], by crowding distance, descending)
    P_{t+1} = P_{t+1} ∪ first (N - |P_{t+1}|) individuals of fronts[i]
    // Increment generation
end
return fronts[1] (Pareto front)
```

Hypervolume Calculation

The hypervolume indicator HV(\mathcal{P}) measures the volume of the objective space dominated by a Pareto front \mathcal{P} with respect to a reference point \mathbf{r} (usually the worst possible point). For two objectives, it is the area of the union of rectangles. For higher dimensions, it is computed via algorithms like the Hypervolume by Slicing Objectives (HSO) or using Monte Carlo sampling.

In AETHER, the reference point is chosen as the vector of worst objective values from the initial population. Convergence is monitored by the relative change in hypervolume over 20 generations.

