Appendix M: Numerical Methods and Finite Element Implementation

The multi-physics simulations are performed using COMSOL Multiphysics with the AC/DC module for electromagnetics and the Structural Mechanics module for stress analysis. The H-formulation is implemented via the PDE interface. The geometry is 2D axisymmetric.

Key implementation details:

· Mesh: Quadrilateral elements with refinement near the coil cross-section and along the axis. Element size ~0.1 mm in the coil, grading to larger elements outside.
· Time stepping: Adaptive time stepping with maximum step 0.1 s during ramp, increasing to 10 s during drift.
· Nonlinear solver: Newton-Raphson with damping; the power law resistivity requires careful initialization. A continuation method in current is used.
· Coupling: The mechanical stress solution is updated at each time step based on the current Lorentz forces; the contact resistivity is updated based on the radial stress.
· Mutual coupling: For multi-pancake models, separate domains are used with coupling through the magnetic vector potential.

For the surrogate modeling, the 320 full FEM simulations were run on a high-performance cluster. Each simulation took approximately 2–4 hours, totaling ~1000 core-hours.

---

Appendix N: Design Space Exploration and Surrogate Modeling Details

The design space has 12 continuous variables (geometric, grading parameters, shim currents, pre-emphasis) and 2 integer variables (N_p, N_f). A Latin hypercube sample of 320 points was generated using the MATLAB function lhsdesign. The bounds for each variable are given in Section 4.1.

The Gaussian process surrogate was built using the fitrgp function in MATLAB's Statistics and Machine Learning Toolbox, with a Matern 5/2 kernel and a separate noise variance for each output. The model was validated using 5-fold cross-validation, yielding R² > 0.95 for all objectives.

NSGA-II was implemented in MATLAB with population size 200, crossover probability 0.9, mutation rate 0.1, and simulated binary crossover (SBX) with distribution index 20. The algorithm ran for 150 generations, with hypervolume computed every 10 generations using the hypervolume function from the PlatEMO toolbox.

