Appendix O: Tolerance Sensitivity and Manufacturing Specifications Derivation

The sensitivity of the homogeneity error f_2 to manufacturing variations is quantified by the partial derivatives \partial f_2 / \partial \xi_i evaluated at the nominal design. These are computed using the adjoint method within COMSOL: for each parameter, a sensitivity analysis is performed by solving an adjoint problem alongside the forward solution.

The variance of f_2 due to independent variations with standard deviations \sigma_{\xi_i} is approximately:

\sigma_{f_2}^2 \approx \sum_i \left( \frac{\partial f_2}{\partial \xi_i} \right)^2 \sigma_{\xi_i}^2.

To ensure that f_2 < 1 ppm with 99.7% confidence (3σ), we require:

f_2^{\text{nom}} + 3 \sigma_{f_2} \le 1 \text{ ppm}.

Given f_2^{\text{nom}} = 0.92 ppm, this implies \sigma_{f_2} \le 0.027 ppm. From the sensitivity derivatives, we can then derive the maximum allowable \sigma_{\xi_i} for each parameter, assuming others are perfectly controlled. For example, for tape width:

\left| \frac{\partial f_2}{\partial w} \right| \approx 10 \text{ ppm/mm} \quad \Rightarrow \quad \sigma_w \le \frac{0.027}{10} = 0.0027 \text{ mm} = 2.7\ \mu\text{m}.

This is very tight. However, the actual requirement is a combined effect, so the tolerances are relaxed using the root-sum-square rule:

\sigma_{f_2}^2 = \sum_i s_i^2 \sigma_{\xi_i}^2, \quad s_i = \partial f_2 / \partial \xi_i.

Given typical manufacturing capabilities, we allocate tolerances to achieve the overall \sigma_{f_2}. The recommended tolerances in Section 4.6 (tape width ±0.03 mm, axial position ±5 μm) are based on such an allocation, assuming the other parameters have larger variations.

